{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e4244cf5-159e-4d14-a641-c3a012cf648d","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events** API in `MauiProgram.cs` (or anywhere you have access to the builder) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs when Android activity is paused\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs when Android activity is stopped\n        }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // runs when iOS app enters background\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` to your `MauiAppBuilder` pipeline in `MauiProgram.cs`.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separated.\n- The delegates give you the native objects (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS) so you can call native APIs if needed.\n- Available via the `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` namespace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36dea91e-d410-4886-a5b3-cbd65d06ea7e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":387,"requestId":"9420:1D5B8A:13FDDC5:166809C:6A067083"},"id":"132b5555-026d-455b-8a52-333a0202dcdb","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:02:02.933Z","parentId":"8bfd5c31-4e6a-425a-9d15-bb42a2305109"}
